A new self-guided campus tour focuses on the role women have played in the history of the built campus environment, with 24 stops featuring women from the 1800s to the present day.

Highlights include the Jordan Schnitzer Museum of Art, whose first director, Gertrude Bass Warner, was a pioneer in museum studies; the Luna sculpture, which was designed by American sculptor and UO graduate Ellen Tykeson; and The Lyllye Reynolds-Parker Black Cultural Center, named after civil rights activist and UO alumna Lyllye Reynolds-Parker.

Click the link in bio to read our Around the O story for more details and visit the Office of Campus Planning website for a link to the tour.

This summer, Emily Norquist, a fourth year neuroscience major who is minoring in psychology, is shadowing Dr. Jason Liauw, a neurosurgeon who specializes in complex and minimally invasive spine surgery at the Saddleback Medical Center in Laguna Hills, California. Emily has the opportunity to observe these surgeries both in the clinic and the operating room.   

After graduation, Emily, who is from from Huntington Beach, Calif., plans on attending medical school. "This experience has truly reestablished my love for medicine and strengthened my desire to pursue a career as a physician," she said.

The Cinema Studies in Ireland study abroad program allows students to mix filmmaking with the study of contemporary Irish cinema. Students live with Irish families in homestays, visit production companies, go on local excursions around the countryside and even take a trip to the Galway Film Fleadh, the country's largest annual film festival.
Here, the study abroad group visits the village of Enniskerry in County Wicklow. It has been transformed into the set of "Disenchanted," the new Disney movie that is the long awaited follow up to "Enchanted." #aroundtheglObe
